DOMAIN: Semiconductor manufacturing process

CONTEXT: A complex modern semiconductor manufacturing process is normally under constant surveillance via the monitoring of signals/ variables collected from sensors and or process measurement points. However, not all of these signals are equally valuable in a specific monitoring system. The measured signals contain a combination of useful information, irrelevant information as well as noise. Engineers typically have a much larger number of signals than are actually required. If we consider each type of signal as a feature, then feature selection may be applied to identify the most relevant signals. The Process Engineers may then use these signals to determine key factors contributing to yield excursions downstream in the process. This will enable an increase in process throughput, decreased time to learning and reduce the per unit production costs. These signals can be used as features to predict the yield type. And by analysing and trying out different combinations of features, essential signals that are impacting the yield type can be identified.

DATA DESCRIPTION: sensor-data.csv : (1567, 592) The data consists of 1567 examples each with 591 features. The dataset presented in this case represents a selection of such features where each example represents a single production entity with associated measured features and the labels represent a simple pass/fail yield for in house line testing. Target column 1 corresponds to a pass and 1 corresponds to a fail and the data time stamp is for that specific test point.

PROJECT OBJECTIVE: We will build a classifier to predict the Pass/Fail yield of a particular process entity and analyse whether all the features are required to build the model or not

Data pre-processing¶

Checking for Null values

In [15]:
def check_forNaN(dataframe):
  na_10=0
  na_100=0
  na_1000=0
  na_more_1000=0
  for i in dataframe.columns:
    col_name=i
    if 1<dataframe[i].isna().sum()<=10:
      na_10+=1
    elif 10<dataframe[i].isna().sum()<=100:
      na_100+=1
    elif 100<dataframe[i].isna().sum()<=1000:
      na_1000+=1
    elif  dataframe[i].isna().sum()>1000:
      na_more_1000+=1 
  if na_10==0 & na_100==0 & na_1000==0 & na_more_1000==0:
    print("No columns have null values")
  else:
    print(na_10," Columns has 10 missing values")  
    print(na_100," Columns has 100 missing values")
    print(na_1000," Columns has 1000 missing values")
    print(na_more_1000," Columns has more than 1000 missing values")
In [16]:
check_forNaN(df)

319  Columns has 10 missing values
75  Columns has 100 missing values
32  Columns has 1000 missing values
20  Columns has more than 1000 missing values

if we directly drop all these rows containing the null values. It would not make any significance as the corresponding rows containing meaningful information would get lost thereby we will lose important data.

So, we can fix this issue with the medians of the corresponding column.

Note: We can also replace them with other values like 0, means, etc but it makes more sense to replace with the median as the distribution of data is more dense around the median unlike the mean which is more likely to be effected by the outliers.

plt.ylabel('Cumalative Varaince Covererd')
plt.show()

Following conclusions can be drawn from the above figure

  • Eigen vectors after 28 starts contributing less than 0.1 to bring down the variance and the values goes on to slow decline as we increase number of eigen vectors.
  • According to the user analogy, one's choice for the number of components may vary.
  • For our convineance we are considering the number of components =40 which explains nearly 60% of the variance.

We can derive following points from the above mentioned graphs:

  • SVC performs better for predicting the true positives in the given dataset.

  • Logistic Regression is able to properly predict 71% of the total Passed Tests but it is able to classify only 50% into the failing Tests scenario.

  • Decision Tree is able to predict only 41% of the total Passed Tests but it is able to classify 62% into the failing Tests scenario which is better than all other Models.

  • Random forest is able to predict only 59% of the total Passed Tests but it is able to classify 38% into the failing Tests scenario

  • SVC is able to predict only 67% of the total Passed Tests but it is able to classify 42% into the failing Tests scenarios.

  • So if the user wants to get a model which is predicting most of pass scenarios then one should go for Logistic Regression but at cost of improper classifying the Failed Scenario.

  • if the user wants to get a model which is predicting most of pass scenarios then one should go for decision tree but at cost of improper classifying the passed Scenario.

  • So this is a trade off between the true positives and true negatives depending on the user but as evident from the ROC curve one can say that the Logistic regression is performing good overall.
